  "A pharmaceutical company wants to test whether a new migraine medication reduces headache duration. They recruit 200 migraine sufferers and randomly assign 100 to receive the medication and 100 to receive a sugar pill. Neither the patients nor the doctors know who receives which pill. After 8 weeks, the average headache duration is 2.1 hours shorter in the medication group. What type of study design is this?": "",
  "A case-control study": "",
  "An observational study": "",
  "A double-blind randomized controlled experiment": "",
  "A voluntary response survey": "",
  "This is a double-blind randomized controlled experiment because subjects are randomly assigned to treatment and control groups, a placebo is used, and neither patients nor doctors know the assignments.": "",
  "A researcher notices that students who eat breakfast tend to have higher GPAs than those who skip breakfast. She concludes that eating breakfast causes better academic performance. What is the main flaw in this reasoning?": "",
  "The sample size is too small to detect a meaningful difference between breakfast and GPA groups": "",
  "She should have used a larger margin of error to account for the natural variability in student GPAs": "",
  "This is an observational study, so confounding variables (like socioeconomic status) may explain the association": "",
  "The study used too much blinding, preventing accurate measurement of the breakfast consumption variable": "",
  "Without random assignment, confounding variables such as household income, parental involvement, or sleep habits could explain the observed association between breakfast and GPA.": "",
  "A school principal wants to test whether a new after-school tutoring program improves math scores. She has 60 students volunteer and lets them choose whether to attend tutoring or not. Students who attend tutoring score 15 points higher on average. Can she conclude the tutoring caused the improvement?": "",
  "No, because students self-selected into groups, introducing confounding variables like motivation": "",
  "Yes, because the difference of 15 points is large": "",
  "Yes, because she had 60 students in the study": "",
  "No, because 60 students is too few for any study": "",
  "Self-selection means more motivated students may have chosen tutoring, and their motivation (not the tutoring itself) could explain the higher scores. Random assignment would be needed for a causal claim.": "",
  "A cosmetics company tests a new anti-aging cream. Group A applies the cream daily, and Group B applies a moisturizer that looks and feels identical but has no active ingredients. Researchers measuring skin elasticity do not know which group each participant belongs to. After 12 weeks, Group A shows a 20% improvement. What role does the identical-looking moisturizer serve?": "",
  "It serves as the explanatory variable": "",
  "It serves as a confounding variable": "",
  "It serves as the placebo to control for the placebo effect": "",
  "It serves as the blocking factor": "",
  "The identical-looking moisturizer without active ingredients is a placebo, ensuring that any measured improvements can be attributed to the active cream rather than the psychological effect of applying a product.": "",
  "An agricultural researcher wants to test three fertilizer types on crop yield. The farm has sections with different soil types (sandy, clay, loamy). She divides each soil section into three plots and randomly assigns one fertilizer to each plot within each section. What experimental design is she using?": "",
  "A completely randomized design": "",
  "A matched-pairs design": "",
  "A randomized block design with soil type as the blocking factor": "",
  "By grouping plots by soil type (blocks) and randomly assigning fertilizers within each block, the researcher uses a randomized block design to control for the confounding effect of soil differences.": "",
  "A fitness company claims their new protein shake builds muscle faster. They recruit 40 gym members and randomly assign 20 to drink the shake daily and 20 to drink a similar-tasting placebo shake. After 3 months, the protein shake group gains an average of 3.2 pounds of muscle while the placebo group gains 2.9 pounds. The difference is not statistically significant (p = 0.42). What should you conclude?": "",
  "The study proves the shake is harmful": "",
  "There is not enough evidence to conclude the shake produces greater muscle gain than the placebo": "",
  "The 0.3-pound difference proves the shake works": "",
  "The protein shake definitively does not work": "",
  "A p-value of 0.42 means the observed difference could easily have occurred by chance. We fail to reject the null hypothesis, meaning there is insufficient evidence that the shake is more effective than the placebo.": "",
  "A sleep researcher wants to compare two types of white noise machines on sleep quality. She pairs 30 participants by age and baseline sleep scores, creating 15 pairs. Within each pair, one person is randomly assigned Machine A and the other Machine B. What design is this?": "",
  "A single-blind observational study": "",
  "A stratified random sampling plan": "",
  "This is a matched-pairs design because participants are paired based on similar characteristics (age and sleep scores), and treatments are randomly assigned within each pair to control for those characteristics.": "",
  "A city health department surveys 5,000 residents and finds that people who live near parks exercise more and have lower rates of heart disease. A newspaper headline reads: 'Living near parks prevents heart disease.' What is wrong with this headline?": "",
  "Parks have nothing to do with health outcomes": "",
  "The margin of error is too large": "",
  "The sample size is too small for any conclusion": "",
  "The study is observational, so it cannot establish that park proximity causes lower heart disease rates": "",
  "This is an observational study, so confounders such as income, lifestyle, and access to healthcare could explain the association. Only a randomized experiment could support a causal claim.": "",
  "A teacher wants to test whether background music helps students concentrate during exams. She teaches two sections of the same course. In Section A, she plays classical music during exams; in Section B, there is silence. Section A scores 5 points higher on average. A classmate argues this is not a valid experiment. Why might the classmate be correct?": "",
  "The sample size is too small": "",
  "Five points is too large a difference to be meaningful": "",
  "Classical music has been proven to always help concentration": "",
  "Students were not randomly assigned to sections, so pre-existing differences between sections could explain the result": "",
  "Without random assignment of students to sections, the groups may differ in ability, motivation, or other factors, making it impossible to attribute the score difference solely to the music.": "",
  "A hospital conducts a study on a new blood pressure medication. They enroll 300 patients with high blood pressure. Patients are randomly assigned to receive either the new medication, the current standard medication, or a placebo. After 6 months, the new medication group has the lowest average blood pressure. How many groups are in this experiment, and what type of control groups are used?": "",
  "1 group: all patients receive the new medication": "",
  "3 groups: new medication (treatment), standard medication (active control), and placebo (placebo control)": "",
  "2 groups: one treatment and one control": "",
  "4 groups: two treatments and two controls": "",
  "There are 3 groups: the new medication is the treatment, the standard medication serves as an active control, and the placebo serves as a placebo control, allowing comparison against both no treatment and existing treatment.": ""
